Pleasant the wind west work in shop finished the jig saw went to the of Lodge of Good Templars
The wind to the southward work in shop making settees for the hall
Moderate and rain in the forenoon . afternoon the wind North West and cold work in shop on settees
The wind North West quite cold in forenoon afternoon moderate. Work in shop making bow drill
Making window frames for Geo. Sargent. The wind south quite cold
The wind. N.W and warm staid at home
The wind W.S.W. morning cold very moderate in afternoon. finished door frames for Geo. Sargent Turning and jigsawing Organ stool etc. for Reuben Rand
The wind very moderate or calm work in shop on boat. Recd letter from Thomas Bunker Cranberry Isles
Calm untill evening then the wind to the eastward. Made a modle for a boat for A Newman
The wind N.W Cold in forenoon made three moulds for a boat went to the Harbor on business
Calm in the morning and pleasant. At noon. The wind ESE snowing and blowing in the evening raining. work in shop on boat
The wind N.W blowed heavy work in shop on boat for A. B. Newman
The wind S.W moderate staid at home
The wind South West in morning SSE in afternoon and rained heavy. Fresh breeze put top gunnels on boat recd letters from C. C. Burrill and Geo. N. Loomis

journal_entry: The wind N.W. work on A. G. Brooks dinner at T. Smallidge's. paid Emmily Mason $.75
The wind N.N.E clear went to Ellsworth in stage dinner at E. Kingsley supper and lodging at City Hotel
The wind W.N.W. fesh breeze Hewed stick timber made ginger bread roller
The wind N.W by W. pointed and headed bolts for the boat putting rail on boat wrote letter to Henry Geyer
E.S.E. Rainy work in shop in forenoon And on A. G. Brooks mainsail in afternoon read package of Liimemnt by Express from H. Geyer
The wind N.W.and.S.W. plowed furrowed and hauled dressing.
notes: wind from 2 directions, changed & to and

journal_entry: The wind southerly and rainy worked in shop making sink and getting out finishing for a butry

The wind North started for Ellsworth went to Lamoine hired team went and went to Ellsworth to see if acct had been settled on J. Moore Estate came back to Lamoine meals on board started for home anchored at stave Island at 12 PM
location: Winter Harbor, Lamoine, Ellsworth, Lamoine, Stave Island

journal_entry: The wind Eastherly and pleasant hauled load of boards for Wm. Dodge in the forenoon in the afternoon work on road with oxen
The wind North west staid at home
The wind North West went a fishing A. squall of rain and hail at night went to Lodge of Good Templars
The wind Southerly worked 1/2 day on A. G. Brooks Galley put foretopmast on Mermaid
The wind southerly and foggy done jig sawing for R. Rand one half day took the boat ashore and cleaned her and hauled of
The wind Northerly strong breeze. went to Crabtrees neck and back in boat. wrote letter to E. Kingsley answered by Kellly Kingsley
notes: changed breese to breeze, not sure if crabtree's neck or crabtree's nook

journal_entry: The wind N.W. commenced haying again put up 28 stacks
The wind South Easterly and rainy went to Mrs. French Temperance lecture in afternoon
The wind Southly and foggy. got one load off hired Saml. Woods team and went home Sold the Mermaid
The wind Southerly went to Bar Harbor to settle with Benj. Kittridge for the Schr Signal and took the Schr. Amulet and came home in her
location: Winter Harbor, Bar Harbor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind Southerly and foggy started to go to Bar Harbor moderate ate and went back finished wheel barrow
location: Winter Harbor, Bar Habor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind South West left home for Jordans river arrived at sunset landed 60 bushels meal for Benj. Kittridge
The wind N.W. got under way and went to Bass Harbor until the wind moderated arrived at home at dark recd letter from Thomas Bunker and Nathan Goodwin
location: Deer Isle, Bass Harbor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind southerly Georgia Foss baby died AM.
The wind N.N.W. could not load recd letter from Perley and Russell wrote letters to Chas Eaton Greens Landing and Benj. Kittridge
The wind Easterly and rainy got under way from Stave Island and came home
The wind Westerly getting ready to go to Rockland filled water repaired boat etc.
The wind very moderate and warm Southerly went to the lower Harbor to see Daniel Southard
The wind North Easterly very moderate hauled the Amulet in the wharf and took out load for myself and J. F. Kingsley. Married Joseph Bickford and Miss Annier Springer recd therefor $2.00
The wind North west made Organ Stool for Montgammery Hammond
The wind North Easterly finished making boxes for wind mill
The wind North West set lamp post for Lodge at Good Templars recd letter from Hanncock Co. publishing company
The wind Northerly and moderate made hammer for horse pistol.
The wind N.N.E. went gunning got one
The wind N.E. overcast walked to W. Gouldsboro got dinner with J. Shaw. took stage to Sullivan walked to S. Franklin in to see Dr. Lewis stoped at the N. E. House all night.
The wind. N.W. Cold cutting wood had four loads hauled home came out at night recd letters from Arno. Wiswell. Wm. Rosebrooks and
The wind N.N.W. smart breeze work on board the Amulet getting pumps clear etc painted the boat inside
The wind W.N.West good breeze hauled Amulet from Tracys Blocks to head of his wharf worked 2 hours and 40 minutes Jig sawing for R. Rand.
The wind S by East and rainy went home by land.
The wind North West very heavy breeze and very cold let go second anchor
The wind Westerly got under way at 10 AM stoped at Cranberry Isles until 3 PM went to N.E. Harbor got my wife and came home at dark
location: Bass Harbor, Cranberry Isles, Northeast Harbor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind Southerly and warm turned Lounge legs for Chas Pendleton snow in afternoon.
The wind N.N.East AM And southerly in afternoon thick snow six inches of snow fell
The wind very moderate to the S.S.E. Wrote letter to Saml. Libby and work on board vessel
The wind East heavy rain all day made ladder and belaying pins for vessel
The wind N.W and S.W work on board vessel gettin ready to go away
Calm in morning in Frenchman's Bay at day light the wind breezed up E.N.E. got in Winter Harbor at 8 oclock A.M.
location: Bass Harbor, Frenchman Bay, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind South West and rough got under way at Stave Island at 3 am, got home in afternoon and rafted apart of the timber ashore foggy
The wind Southerly and Westerly very moderate all day got under way at 10 AM for Salem and anchored in Bass Harbor at 12 mid night very dark and overcast.
The wind southerly hauled of from the wharf
The wind South West heavy rain in afternoon with thunder
The wind North West and pleasant haying hauled in 15 stacks
The wind N. N. E. worked on vessel in forenoon made mast thot in afternoon wrote letter to Hancock Company Pub Co enclosed $1.60
The wind Northerly got in home at 2 AM came out at one PM went through Western way at sunset and anchored in outer Bass Harbor at 12 oclock at night perfectly calm wrote letter to Bangor
location: Schoodic Peninsula, Winter Harbor, Bass Harbor

journal_entry: The wind Northerly went to West Gouldsboro and East sullivan after a load of wood and to settle with James Doyle for a load carried to Boston. wrote letter to E. H. Wallace
location: Winter Harbor, West Gouldsboro, East Sullivan, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind West N West in forenoon W. S. W in afternoon left home at 2 oclock pm for East Sullivan to load with staves for Rockland, arrived at dark and hauled into the wharf
The wind South West and foggy made decoys for Geo Gerrish and dug potatoes wrote letter to Thomas Bunker.
The wind North West in morning got under way in the morning for Rockland in the afternoon the wind hauled South W.  by. W. anchored in Bass Harbor at 4 p.m.
The wind Northerly hauled into the wharf recd letter from Thomas Bunker
The wind W. N. W. heavy blow laid at anchor in Winter Harbor
The wind North West Christmas work in shop
The wind North West dreadful heavy blow and very cold staid in house and taped boots
The wind North East wrote letter to the Secretary of Narraguagus Lodge got the Sea Flower underway and went to South West Harbor and landed freight hauled away from wharf at dark.
location: Winter Harbor, Southwest Harbor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind Westerly moderate wrote letter to Benj. Kittridge work in shop
The wind North West
The wind N.N. W. cold and blustering work turning in shop.
The wind North East moderate rain work in shop on ballance wheel made canvass belt in evening
The wind Westerly good breeze finished saw table recd letter from Benj. Kittridge
The wind North West work in woods cutting wood
The wind North West went in the woods. James Stevens Girl died at 6 P.M.
The wind North West good breeze. snow squalls in morning
The wind Easterly and pleasant. wrote letter to Caroline Blaisdell. work in shop
The wind W. N. W. very heavy blow run wind mill turning belaying pins etc. Recd letter from Capt Thomas Bunker
The wind North East rainy all day untill about sunset. the wind hauling to the North. wrote letters to Thomas Bunker Register of Probate Caroline Blaisdell and Saml. Libby
letter_to: Thomas Bunker, Register of Probate, Caroline Blaisdell, Samuel Libby

journal_entry: The wind Easterly Rainy in forenoon did not work. In the Afternoon held up raining and finished on loading and hauled away from the wharf at night and went to Wehawken to load with coal.
The wind Southerly and foggy work in shop
The wind Southerly and foggy. wrote letters to Mary Am. Rosebrook work in shop
The wind Southerly and foggy. work in garden washed out fish and work in shop finished the Crib.
The wind South and very hot work 1/4 day hewing sleepers for J. R. Hammond house
The wind Southerly Commenced work on T. R. Hammond's. house worked all day
The wind South West work all day on T.R. Hammonds House
The wind Southerly and rainy in afternoon. The wind came of to the North at dark.
The wind W.N.W. work all day on T.R. Hammonds house. putting on finish.
The wind N. West in morning and South West in the afternoon. Splitting wood at the door Alma Torrey Died at 2 p.m.
The wind South Easterly Gathered turnips beets and carrots
The wind Easterly laid at the wharf working on vessel getting ready for sea bound to New York.
Very moderate Southerly attended Wharf meeting
The wind North West work in shop
The wind Westerly work in Shop
The wind South West work on T. H. Smallidges barn all day
The wind North West work in Shop. For myself
The wind Southerly. work in shop building boat
The wind Southerly work in Shop
The wind South West fresh breeze. went down to turtle Isle gunning in forenoon. And in the afternoon went to work claplaeding TH Smallidges barn
location: Winter Harbor, Turtle Island, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind Southerly work in shop
The wind very moderate and overcast all day vary light air Northerly work about home
The wind North went gunning in forenoon. In the afternoon worked for G.W.Tracy on out buildings
The wind North East, and overcast in the afternoon snow storm. Reed deed of Crow Island. from state land agent. work at home in shop and putting besh around the house
The wind Westerly fresh breeze. work in shop.
The wind South West moderate wind and warm. jobbling in shop.

Calm in forenoon wind westerly in afternoon Work building stage in Hall for Exhibition.
The wind North Heavy blow and snow work in forenoon in Shop making Coffin for Ms Danile Southard and in the afternoon work in the Hall makind Scenery frames for Exhibition.

The wind Southerly fresh. breeze and rainy all day went home by land.

journal_entry: The wind North West pleasant Thermometer 32 degrees.
The wind moderate Easterly and fine weather Thermometer 50 Commenced repairing Warren Smith Skiff in the fish house In the Evening Steam boat wharf meeting.
The wind North East Thermometer 18° above and thick with snow all day. Was Power  of Attorny for Capt J B Foss. Reed Card from Wm B Viall
The wind North West. Thermometer 37 degrees Reed letter from Hugh Mckay Lotterie Agent at Canada.
The wind South West and pleasant all day and the Thermometer 37 above. Went to a Religious Meeting in the evening
The wind Westerly and Thermometer 37 degrees wrote letter to Wm B Viall of Bethel Vt. and Auditor of the Treasurer Washington
letter_to: William B. Viall, Auditor of the Treasurer Washington

journal_entry: The wind Westerly Thermometer 18 above Made sinlk for Capt N A Bickford. Reed card from Wm B Viall
The wind South East. and snowing in the morning Went in the woods and got one load of wood at 10 AM heavy rain and spoiled the sleding Thermometer 37°
The wind North East Thermometer 32 degrees snowing moderate all the forenoon. about 18 inches snow fall. The biggest storm for the winter so far. Work 1/2 day for N A Bickford.
The wind West North West. Thermometer 30 degrees worked on half day for N A Bickford and finished work for the present all the lumber used up.
The wind Southerly Thermometer 33 degrees and overcast and the appearances of rain
The wind North West Thermometer at zero in the morning. Made a chart of the mail Routes in Gouldsboro to help establish a Post Office in Birch Harbor Work on Warren Smith boat.
The wind South East Thermometer 47 degrees above Made oath to Amasiah Southard as road surveyer work in forenoon hauling wood for John Gerrish with bled at noon the sun had spoiled the sleding.
The wind North blowing & snowing fearfully The roads blocked with snow so the mail could not go out. the only time for the Winter. Painted my skiff. Thermometer 20° above zero.
The wind North East fresh breeze Thermometer 30 wrote letters to Chas Shaw & Eastern Express Agent at Milbridge Filled out the paper for the new P.O. at Birch Harbor.
THe wind North West. Thermometer 37 degrees Finished making oars.
The wind Westerly and a very fresh breeze Thermometer 20 on the morning. Measured the Black  maniors foremast for a new one.
The wind North East. Thermometer 47 degrees
The wind very moderate South West Thermometer 37 degrees. Went to South Gouldsboro in the forenoon In the afternoon finished hoiking up troll.

The wind South East Thermometer 39 degrees A heavy gale of wind and rain untill afternoon. when it cleared up. And I commenced building fence. on Harbor Point on the line between E.A.Bakers lot & this one.
Wind South West Thermometer. 60° Work about the fish house all day putting it in order to take care of fish.
Wind North Thermometer 45 went to my troll in the morning found moorings parted and apart of the troll in a snarl. Took the troll up carrid it hom cleared it & baited and at night set it.
Wind Westerly Thermometer 65 Registered letter to A.P.Wiswell with $15. enclosed the ballance due on my Insolvency Staid in from fishing to put Cork rope and sinker line on net.
Wind Southerly & foggy Commenced farming plowed all day with the help of Henry Sargent. Acknowledged deed for A.J.Baker Thermometer 65
Wind South West. Thermometer 64 degrees Spaded up the gardens
Wind Southerly, and Thermometer 62 degrees Sowed garden in forenoon and in the afternoon went out and took up my troll. Wrote Deed for R H Bickford
Wind North West in forenoon Thermometer 80° Work the most of the day repairing dora.
Wind North West very fresh breeze to much wind to go a fishing Thermometer 59 work a bout the fish house all day.
The wind South South West Thermometer 79 degrees Went out fishing. foggy in forenoon cleared up in afternoon

Wind Southerly Thermometer 70° Celebrated this day for the fourth. With Yatch races Canoe race by the Indians and foot race. in the evening an Indian Pow wow. and fireworks at Chas Guptill by Mrs Freneck M.D.
The wind Southerly. Thermometer. 60 degrees Foggy. fixed wagon seat for Capt J. P Foss. and mowed some around the door of our house.
The wind Southerly Thick with fog Thermometer 70 degrees went out fishing
The wind North West in the forenoon & South West in afternoon work all day haying hauled in 12 stacks of hay Thermometer 86 degrees at noon
Thick with fog in morning at 10 Am cleared up Went out fishing very fresh breeze Southerly Thermometer 74 degrees
Wind North West all day and very fine weather Thermometer 78°
Calm and thick with fog. Went out fishing heavy rain at noon Thermometer 57 degrees.
Wind Southerly and moderate went out fishing from home in dora. Thermometer 70 degrees.
The wind South West and rough Went to my troll hake very scarce Thermometer in afternoon when I got home 70°
The wind moderate Southerly and moderate rain all day. Thermometer 57 degrees. Work most all day at home on troll.
Wind Southerly Thermometer 50 degrees very fresh breeze and overcast. Work all day on wheel for Capt Sherman Spurling for the Schr Ella heavy shower at night
Moderate Southerly wind all day day thick with fog in the forenoon and clear in the afternoon
Wind Southerly and heavy frost Thermometer 34 in morning Went out fishing got a little. more than one tub of fish. Heavy frost at night.
Wind Northerly in morning went out fishing and swept for the lost troll got it in the afternoon Winf South west. Thermometer 61 degrees,

Wind North West. Thermometer at sun rise 31 degrees. and at noon. 54 degrees. In afternoon wrote deed for E. A. Baker and one for H L Norwood In evening started for Ellsworth Went as for West Gouldsboro
Wind Northerly in morning Thermometer 31° heavy frost. Went out fishing Wind Southerly in afternoon Thermometer 50 degrees
Wind North in morning Thermometer 47 degrees In afternoon wind S. East finished digging my potatoes Geo Gerrish moved in the fish house
The wind Westerly. Thermometer 59 degrees work about home.
Wind Southerly and heavy rain all forenoon at noon cleared up and the sun same out hight
The wind North West. and a very fresh breze at 8 oclock A.M the Thermometer 33 degrees. Work about home all day making soap. Reed the first copy of the New York Weekly sun.
Wind North West very fresh breeze Thermometer in morning 28 degrees. Work apart of the forenoon for Thomas Bickford in afternoon took fish out of bults ready to ship
location: Winter Harbor, Birch Harbor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: Wind North West Thanksgiving day Thermometer 12 above Wrote letter to Dr Porter worked a while in afternoon for J D Harrington.
The wind Northerly in fore noon and hight snow afternoon wind North West Thermometer. 27 degrees work all day getting ready to go with Thomas Smallidge herringing
Wind North North West Thermometer 14 below zero. Ice making very fast. Work about home
Wind Westerly and fresh Thermometer 20' above. Work at home in shop building a wind mill.

Wind Easterly and moderate. the fore part of the day snowy, but in evening wind hauled out South Easterly, and heavy rain. A surprise party atour house in the evening consisting of 12 people I have been busy this day in shop on wind mill.
Wind North in morning Thermometer 4' below zero. Noon wind East and at 4 PM wind South Easterly. Evening snow storm Work in shop at home
Wind Northerly Fresh. and the Thermometer below zero all day To cold to work in shop. and staid in the house most of the time
Wind North West work about home at night wind Southerly Evening went to the Hall to Masonic meeting No snow on the ground on ice around the shores

Wind Westerly thick with snow in morning. At 8 AM cleared up. Went to Franklin with Capt. Nathan A. Bickford. with John Sargents horse. No business in particular. Took dinner at the Relay House. Got back home at dark.
Wind Easterly hauled through the last Bridge coming from Cambridge port and went into Union wharf for freight as the wind was Easterly. At night had all the freight in ready to sail for home

Wind Easterly and overcast. About home. worked apart of the day digging potatoes for Jennie Kingsley. Sent Ambrose Springers horse home by my mate Lewis Fross. as I do not intend to go back to Franklin to join the Chromo for a few days
Wind North West heavy, laid at wharf East Boston all day, bound home. the wind blowing to hard to move

Wind Westerly and a very fresh breeze Got underway at Bass Harbor in the forenoon. and went home. In the afternoon the wind moderated. And got Capt. H. E. Tracy to take the vessel to go a trip as it is to early to haul up. and I do not care to go away again myself

Wind North West. very heavy. The tug boat could not tow the Chromo from the wharf at Franklin, and my servises being no longer needed I walk to Sullivan take the Steam boat to So. Gouldsboro and go home. As I do not wish to go away again this fall H E Tracy goes the trip for me.
Wind North East Sleet storm. Helped Capt. Chas David haul his vessel up to my wharf.
Wind N.N.E and overcast Staid about home all day.
Took 1043 lbs lobsters to factory went to West Gouldsboro took dinner with John Shaw got some plank and went home
location: Winter Harbor, West Gouldsboro, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: Stormy work in shop reed letter from CC Burrill also oil painting of Niagara Falls by moon light went to Lodge of G. Templar lodgign at Thos. Smallidge
notes: This oil painting of Niagara Falls by moon light actually exists, so cool! by Hermann Herzog. Little random in text though..

journal_entry: Work about home and in the shop
About home went to the Lodge installed officers had supper
Work in shop reed letter from Hale & Emery went to Lodge of G.T. reed letter from Hale & Emery
The wind to the southward foggy and rainy work in shop making setees for the Hall
notes: changed fogy to foggy, changed & to and, assumed N for Southward am

journal_entry: The wind N.W. quite moderate made pump box and belaying pins for James Stevens
The wind Northwest cold made gun screw for J. F. Kingsley
The wind to the South and warm putting framed together in forenoon
The wind N.W. and Extremely cold work in shop in forenoon making door frames Went to Capt T. R. Hammond's navigation school in evening
The wind N. blow heavy great abundance of snow fell work in shop on boat J. F. Kingsley finish sash for John Shaw
The wind N.E chilly made saw horse and wood saw frame for Thomas Smallidge
Calm and warm work in shop on boat
The wind W.N.W at work in shop done some turning for Reuben Rand and working on boat
The wind N.W blowed heavy turning posts for boat rail
Southerly is the wind thunder and rain at night hauled out ten load of dressing for oats. Recd garden seeds from Marblehead went to Lodge of Good Templars
The wind southerly made damper for stove pipe wrote letter to Proctor Smallidge
The wind North West commenced making lamppost for Good Templars
The wind North East went to Prospect in stage after yoke of oxen Engaged. Evans Young. went to Lodge of Good Templars Elected Officers.
The wind North West cold work in shop.
The wind W.N.W. good breeze worked all day Jigs awing finish for R. Rands house three fourths day
The wind southerly and warm made caulking mallet and fixed dora getting ready to go across to Cranberry Isles after the Sea Flower. Went to Lodge of Good Templars was Worthy Chief protem
The wind Southerly and warm worked all day with Wm. Guptill caulking Sea Flower went to Lodge of Good Templars and Elected officers
The wind N.N.W. and very pleasant hauled from the wharf into the Harbor and put Bed clotes and chest on board.
The wind Southerly and foggy rafted the remainder of the timber ashore and made a spoke for the vessel's wheel
The wind south west hauled into the wharf to stop a leak and work on the vessel.
The wind Southerly work on vessel painting scaping etc. recd letter from Charly Burrill.
The wind Southwest foggy finished hanging rudder
The wind Northerly hauled the vessel into the wharf.

The wind Southerly and foggy bought a stick of Win Rand to make a flying jib boom in forenoon and went to work making it with J. f. Kingsley in afternoon wrote letters to Robt Miles and Nickerson and Rideout
The wind North W. wrote ltter to Capt Thomas Smallidge work in shop
The wind North West cold and blowy issued warrant for Hall meeting to be called Jan 22
The wind N West made Axe handle getting ready to go in woods
very moderate wind Northerly turning Iron for shafts for saw
The wind Westerly went in the woods cutting firewood
The wind S.S.East snowy commenced making wheel for Black Warrior
The wind very moderate South West and very warm snow melts fast.  wrote letter to Thomas Bunker recd one from Benj. Kittridge. work in shop
The wind North West cold. work in shop commenced building a dora.
The wind Easterly and warm.
The wind W. N. W. heavy blow jobbing in shop
The wind North West work in shop finished jib sawing for G. W. Whitaker
The wind Easterly and foggy and rainy put down a mooring for a boat. and work in shop.
The wind Southerly and foggy and rainy work in shop.
The wind Southerly and foggy work sawing wood
The wind N.E. Help make Casket for Alma Torrey
The wind Southerly and foggy work in shop
The wind out Southerly in afternoon foggy Fixed well bucket and work in shop
The wind Southerly work in Shop making window frames for T.H. Smallidge
The wind Southerly work in Shop
The wind Southerly work in Shop
The wind S.S.East. and rainy in the forenoon work in shop on boat.
Heavy breeze to the Westward work in the shop
The wind Westerly work in shop turning wood the wind mill
The wind moderate all day Southerly wrote letter to Charles Peter Bangor. work in shop making Closet for W.M Pendleton
Very moderate all day wind Northerly. Went Clam turing and floundering in the forenoon and in the afternoon work at home in the shop

journal_entry: The Thermometer 55 degrees above zero Calm and pleasant. Made two sliding sleds for children.
The wind Westerly and Thermometer 35 degrees Went to a Religious meeting in the evening at the Hall
The wind North East & South Thermometer 43° Turned Lounge legs for R Rand. in forenoon and traded my row boat called the Stella with Warren Smith for a skiff work repairing her in the afternoon.
The wind North West. and a fresh breeze Thermometer. 24 degrees in shade. Work in the afternoon turning heads for wheel barrow fro R Rand.
The wind from North East to North West Thermometer 30° made rudder Irons for boat and made mast.
Wind Easterly and heavy rain all day. Thermometer. 52 degrees. Work in afternoon For F. H. Smallidge hewing nails for fence.
Calm in morning Wind Southerly in afternoon finished repairing dora and set net at night Thermometer 68 degrees.
Took 1261 lbs lobsters to factory came home went to Lodge
The wind to the southward work in shop making settees for the hall
Moderate and rain in the forenoon . afternoon the wind North West and cold work in shop on settees
The wind North West quite cold in forenoon afternoon moderate. Work in shop making bow drill
Making window frames for Geo. Sargent. The wind south quite cold
The wind W.S.W. morning cold very moderate in afternoon. finished door frames for Geo. Sargent Turning and jigsawing Organ stool etc. for Reuben Rand
The wind very moderate or calm work in shop on boat. Recd letter from Thomas Bunker Cranberry Isles
The wind W. quite cold finished the schr Virgins boat. Went to Hall Meeting in evening and was chosen treasurer for the ensuing year
Calm untill evening then the wind to the eastward. Made a modle for a boat for A Newman
The wind North and warm filed wood saw for Ambrose Bourgett made shoe for the A. G. Brooks anchor went to Lodge of Good Templars
Calm in the morning and pleasant. At noon. The wind ESE snowing and blowing in the evening raining. work in shop on boat
The wind N.W blowed heavy work in shop on boat for A. B. Newman
The wind South West in morning SSE in afternoon and rained heavy. Fresh breeze put top gunnels on boat recd letters from C. C. Burrill and Geo. N. Loomis
letter_from: Charles C. Burill, George N. Loomis

journal_entry: The wind N.W. work on A. G. Brooks dinner at T. Smallidge's. paid Emmily Mason $.75
The wind W.N.W. fesh breeze Hewed stick timber made ginger bread roller
The wind N.W by W. pointed and headed bolts for the boat putting rail on boat wrote letter to Henry Geyer
E.S.E. Rainy work in shop in forenoon And on A. G. Brooks mainsail in afternoon read package of Liimemnt by Express from H. Geyer
The wind southerly and rainy worked in shop making sink and getting out finishing for a butry
The wind North West went a fishing A. squall of rain and hail at night went to Lodge of Good Templars
The wind southerly and foggy done jig sawing for R. Rand one half day took the boat ashore and cleaned her and hauled of
The wind Northerly strong breeze. went to Crabtrees neck and back in boat. wrote letter to E. Kingsley answered by Kellly Kingsley
notes: changed breese to breeze, not sure if crabtree's neck or crabtree's nook

journal_entry: The wind North Easterly finished making boxes for wind mill
The wind North West set lamp post for Lodge at Good Templars recd letter from Hanncock Co. publishing company
The wind Northerly and moderate made hammer for horse pistol.
The wind. N.W. Cold cutting wood had four loads hauled home came out at night recd letters from Arno. Wiswell. Wm. Rosebrooks and
The wind Southerly and warm turned Lounge legs for Chas Pendleton snow in afternoon.
The wind East heavy rain all day made ladder and belaying pins for vessel
The wind southerly hauled of from the wharf
The wind South West and foggy made decoys for Geo Gerrish and dug potatoes wrote letter to Thomas Bunker.
The wind Northerly hauled into the wharf recd letter from Thomas Bunker
The wind North West Christmas work in shop
The wind North East wrote letter to the Secretary of Narraguagus Lodge got the Sea Flower underway and went to South West Harbor and landed freight hauled away from wharf at dark.
location: Winter Harbor, Southwest Harbor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind Westerly moderate wrote letter to Benj. Kittridge work in shop
The wind N.N. W. cold and blustering work turning in shop.
The wind North East moderate rain work in shop on ballance wheel made canvass belt in evening
The wind Westerly good breeze finished saw table recd letter from Benj. Kittridge
The wind Easterly and pleasant. wrote letter to Caroline Blaisdell. work in shop
The wind W. N. W. very heavy blow run wind mill turning belaying pins etc. Recd letter from Capt Thomas Bunker
The wind Southerly and foggy work in shop
The wind Southerly and foggy. wrote letters to Mary Am. Rosebrook work in shop
The wind Southerly and foggy. work in garden washed out fish and work in shop finished the Crib.
The wind South and very hot work 1/4 day hewing sleepers for J. R. Hammond house
The wind Southerly Commenced work on T. R. Hammond's. house worked all day
The wind South West work all day on T.R. Hammonds House
The wind Southerly and rainy in afternoon. The wind came of to the North at dark.
The wind W.N.W. work all day on T.R. Hammonds house. putting on finish.
Very moderate Southerly attended Wharf meeting
The wind North West work in shop
The wind Westerly work in Shop
The wind South West work on T. H. Smallidges barn all day
The wind North West work in Shop. For myself
The wind Southerly. work in shop building boat
The wind Southerly work in Shop
The wind South West fresh breeze. went down to turtle Isle gunning in forenoon. And in the afternoon went to work claplaeding TH Smallidges barn
location: Winter Harbor, Turtle Island, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: The wind Southerly work in shop
The wind North went gunning in forenoon. In the afternoon worked for G.W.Tracy on out buildings
The wind North East, and overcast in the afternoon snow storm. Reed deed of Crow Island. from state land agent. work at home in shop and putting besh around the house
The wind Westerly fresh breeze. work in shop.
The wind South West moderate wind and warm. jobbling in shop.
notes: wind direction entered in am as does not specify time of day, same with wind speed and weather cond

journal_entry: The wind Southerly and in the afternoon rainy work in shop
notes: wind direction entered in am as does not specify time of day

journal_entry: The wind fresh North West. work in shop turing wheel hubs for Capt Nahum Rosebooks. in the evening played at the Exhibition in evening.
notes: wind direction entered in am as does not specify time of day, same with weather speed

journal_entry: The wind Southerly Heavy rain all day work in shop
notes: wind direction entered in am as does not specify time of day

journal_entry: The wind South East and rainy all day. reed lettre from Lee Narraguagus Lodge. work in shop
notes: wind direction entered in am as does not specify time of day

journal_entry: The wind moderate Easterly and fine weather Thermometer 50 Commenced repairing Warren Smith Skiff in the fish house In the Evening Steam boat wharf meeting.
The wind Westerly Thermometer 18 above Made sinlk for Capt N A Bickford. Reed card from Wm B Viall
The wind South East. and snowing in the morning Went in the woods and got one load of wood at 10 AM heavy rain and spoiled the sleding Thermometer 37°
The wind North East Thermometer 32 degrees snowing moderate all the forenoon. about 18 inches snow fall. The biggest storm for the winter so far. Work 1/2 day for N A Bickford.
The wind West North West. Thermometer 30 degrees worked on half day for N A Bickford and finished work for the present all the lumber used up.
The wind South East Thermometer 47 degrees above Made oath to Amasiah Southard as road surveyer work in forenoon hauling wood for John Gerrish with bled at noon the sun had spoiled the sleding.
The wind North blowing & snowing fearfully The roads blocked with snow so the mail could not go out. the only time for the Winter. Painted my skiff. Thermometer 20° above zero.
THe wind North West. Thermometer 37 degrees Finished making oars.

The wind South East Thermometer 39 degrees A heavy gale of wind and rain untill afternoon. when it cleared up. And I commenced building fence. on Harbor Point on the line between E.A.Bakers lot & this one.
Wind South West Thermometer. 60° Work about the fish house all day putting it in order to take care of fish.
Wind South West. Thermometer 64 degrees Spaded up the gardens
Wind Southerly, and Thermometer 62 degrees Sowed garden in forenoon and in the afternoon went out and took up my troll. Wrote Deed for R H Bickford
Wind North West in forenoon Thermometer 80° Work the most of the day repairing dora.
Wind North West very fresh breeze to much wind to go a fishing Thermometer 59 work a bout the fish house all day.

Wind Southerly Thermometer 70° Celebrated this day for the fourth. With Yatch races Canoe race by the Indians and foot race. in the evening an Indian Pow wow. and fireworks at Chas Guptill by Mrs Freneck M.D.
The wind Southerly. Thermometer. 60 degrees Foggy. fixed wagon seat for Capt J. P Foss. and mowed some around the door of our house.
Wind Southerly Thermometer 50 degrees very fresh breeze and overcast. Work all day on wheel for Capt Sherman Spurling for the Schr Ella heavy shower at night
Wind North in morning Thermometer 47 degrees In afternoon wind S. East finished digging my potatoes Geo Gerrish moved in the fish house
Wind North West very fresh breeze Thermometer in morning 28 degrees. Work apart of the forenoon for Thomas Bickford in afternoon took fish out of bults ready to ship
location: Winter Harbor, Birch Harbor, Winter Harbor

journal_entry: Wind North West Thanksgiving day Thermometer 12 above Wrote letter to Dr Porter worked a while in afternoon for J D Harrington.
Wind NorthWest fresh. Work in shop at home. In evening went to the Hall to a Masonic meeting of instructions myself master Opened on the first degree & initiated a candidate
Wind Southerly and rainy all day. work in the shop at home. In the evening went to the Hall to see the presents on the Christmas tree
Pleasant the wind west work in shop finished the jig saw went to the of Lodge of Good Templars
The wind N.W Cold in forenoon made three moulds for a boat went to the Harbor on business
The wind very moderate and warm Southerly went to the lower Harbor to see Daniel Southard
